Factors Influencing the Executive and Legislative Conflict in Nigeria Political Development\'94}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f0\insrsid2910923  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\insrsid2910923 (2016) 21(8) IOSR }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f0\insrsid2910923 Journal of Humanities and Social Science}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\insrsid2910923 , 20-25 at 20}}}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\cf1\insrsid2910923\charrsid9131397 
 This theory implies that different bodies of persons should perform the three functions of the government. Each department (the legislature, the executive, and the judiciary) limited to its sphere of actions and wit
hin that field should be independent and supreme\'94
. The essence of the theory of separation of powers, therefore, is built on the believe that, if the executive, legislature, and the judiciary powers are vested in one person or group of individuals, such pe
ople will have unlimited powers. In such a way that they could prescribe any law, arrest anyone and even prosecute same for no reason. Since they exercise unlimited powers. Through the separation of powers then, any particular group cannot prescribe, exec
ute and adjudicate in any case at the same time.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs41\f0\fs24\cf1\super\insrsid2910923\charrsid9131397 \chftn {\footnote\ftnalt \ltrpar \pard\plain \ltrpar
