defined "separation of powers" as the practice of dividing the powers of a government among different branches thereof. He equated it to the principle of "division of labour" in Adam Smith\rquote 
s economics, and he termed it as a liberty-sensitive concept. He juxtaposes between the "horizontal" separation of powers and "vertical" separation of powers 
\par He traced the evolution of the concept from the British Parliament\rquote s gradual assertion of power and resistance to the royal decrees during the 14}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\super\insrsid2910923\charrsid9131397 th}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid2910923\charrsid9131397  Century where the English scholar, James Harrington, was one of the first modern philosophers to analyze the
 Doctrine in his essay, "Commonwealth of Oceana" (1656), he traced it to John Locke, who he said gave the separation concept more refined treatment in his Second Treatise on Government (1690). He further traced it to Baron de Montesquieu The Spirit of Law
s (1748), He stated that all the scholars saw the concept of separation of powers as a way to reduce or eliminate the arbitrary powers of unchecked rulers. 
\par He related Separation of powers to the doctrine of "checks and balances". He examined the criticism 
of the doctrine which stated strong democracies like United Kingdom which operates without separation of powers. He responded that a total absence of separation of powers, often figures prominently in extreme repressive governments like China, Czechoslova
kia, Poland, and Russia were ruled by communist governments for part of the 20th Century, and an absence of separation of powers in these regimes made it easier for leaders to abuse their authority. 
\par He further examined Separation of power in the present }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid2910923\charrsid9131397 1999 Constitution of the Federal Republic of Nigeria}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 
