e established the Horizontal and vertical separation of power in the Constitution and he further clarified that there is no complete and total separation of powers in Nigeria. He discussed instances where the Constitution made provision for overlap of pow
ers, he continued by discussing exhaustively the Separation of power under the military regimes with relevant cases and examples to show the doctrine\rquote 
s non-existence during those regimes. He also discussed some abuse of the doctrine in the Civilian Regimes 
such as the declaration of state of emergency in Plateau State by the federal government on May 18, 2004. He concluded that a genuine practice of separation of powers is germane to the sustenance and survival of democracy in Nigeria.
