\par }\pard \ltrpar\s18\qj \li0\ri0\sb100\sa100\sbauto1\saauto1\sl360\slmult1\widctlpar\wrapdefault\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid9131397 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\cf0\insrsid2910923\charrsid9131397 To discover the const
itutional principles which best promoted political liberty, Montesquieu looked to the English Constitution which in his belief, was the only one having liberty as its chief object. Though the English constitution classified political power primarily in te
rms of \lquote legislative\rquote  and \lquote executive\rquote  functions and further sub-divided the latter to take into account Locke\rquote s distinction between \lquote executive\rquote  and \lquote federative\rquote 
 functions, he decided to call the conduct of foreign affairs as \lquote executive power\rquote  and the execution of domestic law as \lquote judicial power\rquote 
. It is based on this broad classification that he divided governmental power into legislative, executive and judicial functions. Of the trio, he considered judicial power as the most frightening power since in his opi
nion executive could not harm a subject\rquote 
s life, liberty or property until after a judicial decision. His idea of separation of powers was a major influence on the founders and framers of the American constitution. Article I; Section 1 vests all legislative
 powers in the Congress. Article II; section 1 vest all executive powers in the President and Article III; Section 1 vests all judicial powers in the Supreme Court. 
\par Despite the safeguards against tyranny, the modern-day societies find it difficult to apply the doctrine rigidly. While America adopts the doctrine with only slight modifica
tions, the United Kingdom follows a parliamentary form of government where the Crown is the nominal head and the real legislative functions are performed by the Parliament. The existence of a cabinet system refutes the doctrine of separation of powers com
p
letely. It is the cabinet which is the real head of the executive, instead of the Crown. It initiates legislations, controls the legislature and even holds the power to dissolve the assembly. The vesting of two powers in a single body, therefore denies th
e fact that there is any kind of separation of powers in England.
\par Authors who believe there is an application of the doctrine in the modern United Kingdom have described only the independence of the judiciary as evidence that the model applies. The influenc
e of the doctrine of separation of powers to the Nigerian Constitution is to a large extent based on the American understanding of it. This is clearly discernible in the Constitutions of 1979 and 1999.
\par  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f0\cf0\insrsid2910923\charrsid9131397 2.2 CONCEPT OF SEPARATION OF POWERS }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\cf0\insrsid2910923\charrsid9131397 
\par The rationale behind the doctrine of separation of powers is that neither the legislature, the executive nor the judiciary should exercise the whole or part of another\rquote 
s powers, but it does not exclude checks by one branch over the other. In the United State and Nigeria, 
separation of powers is understood to mean an executive composed of non-parliamentary members. These States practice a presidential system of government where executive powers are vested in the president who has a cabinet made of the heads of departments 
under the executive arm. The heads of departments are personally responsible to the President and neither to the Congress nor the National Assembly.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af39 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs41\f0\cf0\super\insrsid2910923\charrsid9131397 \chftn {\footnote\ftnalt 
