Political liberty is to be found only when there is no abuse of power. But constant experience shows us that every man invested with power is liable to abuse it, and to carry 
his authority as far as it will go. To prevent this abuse, it is necessary from the very nature of things that one power should be a check on another. When the legislative and executive powers are united in the same person or body there can be no liberty.
 Again, there is no liberty if the judicial power is not separated from the legislature and executive. There would be an end to everything if the same person or body, whether of the nobles or of the people, were to exercise all these powers.\'94}{
