\par The Constitution provides that the abovenamed Officers may only be removed from offi
ce where they have been found guilty of gross misconduct in the performance of the functions of their office. Since 1999 however, accusing fingers have been pointed at the executive at the Federal level of being responsible for the removal of some governo
rs which negates the principle of \lquote vertical\rquote  separation of powers. It is being known that the President propels the members of the State House of Assembly to remove their Governor while such members under the guise of \lquote 
gross misconduct\rquote  do the removing. The eventual result is that the legislators rush to remove their governors thereby tainting the removal process with constitutional irregularities. 
\par This was the case in Anambra State where President Obasanjo was accused of being responsible for the removal o
