 At the State level, the appointment of top judicial officers is made by the Governor of the State on the recommendation of the National Judicial
 Council. It is submitted that this process is not healthy for the doctrine of separation of powers. This is so because as politicians, the President and members of the National Assembly or Governor and members of the State House of Assembly may be swayed
 to make such appointments on political connections, religious leanings, \'93federal character\'94 without any regard for merit and competence. Where this is done, the consequence is the proverbial \'93he who pays the piper dictates the tune.\'94 
